📘 Section 07 — Entra ID Security

Chapter 01 — Entra ID Security Fundamentals (Single Sub‑Section)


🔰 1) Introduction
Microsoft Entra ID (formerly Azure AD) is the cloud identity backbone for authentication, authorization, and access governance across Microsoft 365, Azure, SaaS apps, and hybrid identity.
Security in Entra ID revolves around enforcing strong authentication, eliminating legacy risks, controlling privileged access, protecting tokens, and continuously monitoring user risk and sign‑in behavior.
This chapter provides a single, consolidated overview of Entra ID Security essential for Zero Trust.

🧠 2) Why Entra ID Security Matters
Modern attacks no longer begin at the firewall — they begin with identity.
Attackers frequently target:

Passwords (spray, brute force, replay)
Refresh tokens & browser cookies
OAuth app consent
Misconfigured Conditional Access
Over‑permissioned service principals
Legacy authentication endpoints
Privileged roles without governance

A compromise in Entra ID = compromise of email, Teams, OneDrive, SharePoint, Azure resources, and often on‑prem AD through hybrid sync.
Identity is the control plane, and securing it is the foundation of Zero Trust.

🧩 3) Core Pillars of Entra ID Security
1. Strong Authentication

Enforce MFA for all users
Prefer passwordless (FIDO2, Authenticator app, Windows Hello for Business)
Block legacy authentication
Protect refresh tokens with CAE (Continuous Access Evaluation)

2. Conditional Access Policies
Evaluates identity, device, app, location, and risk in real-time.
Key CA principles:

Require MFA
Require compliant or hybrid‑joined device
Block high-risk sign-ins
Restrict access from specific countries/locations
Allow only modern authentication

3. Privileged Access Governance

Use PIM (Privileged Identity Management) for Just‑In‑Time elevation
Remove persistent Global Admin / App Admin roles
Use separate admin workstations
Audit privileged role assignments monthly

4. Identity Protection
AI-driven risk engine analyzing:

Leaked credentials
Impossible travel
Malware/anonymous IP sign-ins
Atypical sign-in behavior
Token replay indicators

Risk-based policies (User Risk/Sign-In Risk) block or challenge access automatically.
5. Application Security

Restrict user consent
Require admin approval for app permissions
Remove stale enterprise applications
Use certificate credentials instead of client secrets
Monitor app API permissions (highest stealth escalation path)

6. Device & Session Security

Require compliant devices
Use Conditional Access session restrictions
Integrate with Defender for Cloud Apps for data loss prevention
EnForce real-time controls (block downloads, watermarking, limited sessions)


🏗️ 4) How Entra ID Defends the Identity Lifecycle
[User Sign-in]
    │
    ▼
[MFA / Passwordless] — Prevent credential compromise
    │
    ▼
[Conditional Access] — Apply Zero Trust rules
    │
    ▼
[Token Issuance + CAE] — Protect and monitor tokens
    │
    ▼
[Risk Engine] — Analyze sign-in/user risk
    │
    ▼
[Privileged Access (PIM)] — Time-bound elevation
    │
    ▼
[Audit Logs + Alerts] — Detection & response

This pipeline ensures identity is validated, contextualized, and continuously reassessed.

🔐 5) Common Entra ID Attack Paths (Awareness)
1. Token Replay
Stolen refresh tokens reused on unmanaged endpoints.
2. Illicit Consent Grant / OAuth Abuse
Malicious apps gaining high‑privilege API permissions.
3. MFA Fatigue
Repeated MFA prompts lead to accidental approval.
4. Password Spray
Wide username list + one common password.
5. Rogue Service Principals
Compromised app identity maintains persistent access.
6. Legacy Auth Bypass
Basic Auth + SMTP/POP/IMAP allow password-only sign-ins.

🛡️ 6) Hardening & Best Practices (Operational Playbook)
✔ Strong Authentication

Enforce MFA everywhere
Convert admins to passwordless
Block legacy authentication globally

✔ Conditional Access (baseline)

Require MFA
Require compliant devices
Block risky sign-ins
Require trusted networks for admin roles
Set sign‑in frequency and token lifetime controls

✔ App Security

Block user consent
Require verified publishers
Audit app permissions monthly
Migrate client secrets → certificates

✔ Privileged Access

Enable PIM
No standing admin roles
Monitor elevation requests
Use separate admin credentials and PAWs

✔ Logging & Monitoring
Enable Diagnostic Settings to send logs to:

Log Analytics
Sentinel
Event Hub (SIEM integration)

Log categories:

Sign-in logs
Audit logs
Provisioning logs
Risky sign-ins
Identity Protection insights


🛠️ 7) Troubleshooting & Incident Detection
Key Logs

Sign-in logs: See CA evaluation, MFA, token details
Audit logs: See admin changes, role assignments, app configuration
Identity Protection: Root cause for risky sign-ins
App consent events: Detect OAuth abuse

Troubleshooting Scenarios
Scenario A — User blocked unexpectedly

Check CA evaluation reasons
Check risk score (Identity Protection)
Device compliance status

Scenario B — MFA prompt loop

Multiple CA policies conflicting
Non-modern client apps triggering legacy auth

Scenario C — Suspicious sign-in

Check risk detection
Review token signing logs
Map unusual IP / device fingerprint


🧾 8) Summary
Entra ID Security is the core layer of Zero Trust, providing authentication strength, risk assessment, privileged identity governance, and application control.
A strong Entra ID Security posture includes:

MFA & passwordless
Conditional Access enforcement
PIM for admin roles
Identity Protection for risk-based blocking
Restrictive app permission model
Full logging + monitoring through Sentinel

Entra ID is the first and most important perimeter in today’s security landscape.
